---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import BlogHero from '../../components/BlogHero.astro';
import BlogFigure from '../../components/BlogFigure.astro';
import RelatedPosts from '../../components/RelatedPosts.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug, postsBySlugs, RELATED_POSTS } from '../../data/posts';

const post = postBySlug('acoustic-slat-wall-panels-tv-mount-kilmarnock')!;
const relatedPosts = postsBySlugs(RELATED_POSTS[post.slug] ?? []).slice(0, 3);
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${BASE}/gallery/kilmarnock-acoustic-slat-wall-panelling-tv-mount-05-1600w.jpg`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: { '@type': 'Person', name: post.author, worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` } },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  keywords: [post.keyword],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="article"
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        A feature-wall job in a Kilmarnock home: full-height acoustic slat
        panels across one wall, the TV wall-mounted over the top, a floating
        shelf underneath and the new light fittings hung at either end.
      </p>
    </header>

    <BlogHero slug="kilmarnock-acoustic-slat-wall-panelling-tv-mount-05" />

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg cv-auto">
      <h2>What the job involved</h2>
      <p>
        Slat panels look simple but they are only as good as what sits behind
        them. We marked out the stud line first, fixed a felt-backed batten
        grid, and then ran the panels top to bottom with tight seams at the
        corners. The TV bracket went in before the panels closed over it, so
        the fixings caught solid timber rather than the slats.
      </p>
      <p>
        Power and aerial feeds were dropped inside the batten cavity so nothing
        runs on the surface. Once the wall was on, the floating shelf went up
        on hidden brackets, and the pair of light fittings either side of the
        TV were hung and tested.
      </p>

      <BlogFigure slug="kilmarnock-acoustic-slat-wall-panelling-tv-mount-05" />

      <h2>Things to think about before you start</h2>
      <p>
        Pick the wall for acoustic slats with the TV placement and daylight in
        mind — a wall that catches strong morning sun will wash out the colour
        of the felt backing, and a TV mounted opposite a big window will always
        fight glare. Think about cable routes too: running power, aerial and
        HDMI inside the cavity is straightforward on day one and awkward later.
      </p>
      <p>
        Check the wall is sound before any panels go up. Old plaster that is
        hollow behind, or a stud wall with voids in the wrong spots, will force
        you to over-batten. It is not difficult but it changes what you are
        buying, so it is worth a proper look before the work starts.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you are in Kilmarnock and need something similar, Fraser will come
        and look for free. Call <strong>07900 255876</strong> or WhatsApp
        <strong>+44 7472 223323</strong>. FREE no-obligation quote, every job
        priced individually.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  {relatedPosts.length > 0 && (
    <RelatedPosts posts={relatedPosts} eyebrow="Keep reading" heading="Related posts" variant="tinted" />
  )}

  <CTABlock
    heading="Thinking about a feature wall?"
    sub="Send a photo of the wall and we will come and talk it through."
    location="Kilmarnock"
  />
</BaseLayout>
